</B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>I live here.... get out.</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>4/18/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#000033>11:43:03 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Shields</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">I never use a shield. And I assume that goes for the vast majority of rangers here. However, today it hit me that I really ought to keep one around for a particular situation, which is during high end fights using Trueshot. <br>
<br>
Since I am not in any way profiting from a weapon in my offhand when using a bow (Unlike if I had epics, where the haste on Swiftwind would make a large difference), why not get hold of a shield with some good ac, or even better, good resists, and put it there? When that hit me it was like 'Duh, why on earth didn't I think of this before, it's so obvious'... well, it wasn't to me, being so used to dual wielding that the thought of a shield never even occurred to me. <br>
<br>
So thats my advice of the day for non epic 55+ rangers, go get hold of a shield with resists (Can a ranger use a Shield of Rainbow Hues? Not that I would be able to get one, but that would be perfect. Otherwise even a Shiny Brass Shield would be great, +10mr) and use it when you're playing artillery in a fight. It will help you live longer against mobs with an AoE attack, or avoid getting feared by mobs that like to do that. And once you've used up trueshot, just get out your regular weapons and go melee the bastard, being in better shape at this point than you would have been without your shield.<br>
<br>
Also, for us non epic rangers out there, getting a Wurmslayer and placing it in your primary hand would additionally enhance your survivability, with its 5ac and 5mr. Not to mention the str bonus which may/may not increase damage from your bow. I have a feeling strength has a small effect on archery damage, but at this point that is no more that a hunch.<br>
<br>
Anyways, I hope this will enlighten any rangers out there who have so far been as oblivious to the advantages of a shield as I used to be <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
